WEBVTT

00:15.488 --> 00:21.333
You were born in Rockdale? I was here at the mine, 
the broken mine. You were born at the old mine?

00:27.738 --> 00:28.919
Yeah, I was born there. I was raised and born there. 
I lived in Bonne Conde all my life. How old were you

00:34.464 --> 00:37.947
when you went into the mines? What? How old were you 
when you went into the mines? I was about 18 when I

00:40.930 --> 00:42.030
worked in there. I worked in there about six months 
here. I wasn't old enough, you know. I worked about

00:46.910 --> 00:48.753
six months. I went down there with Daddy, you know. 
Your dad? I went down to Lexington. Yeah, Daddy,

00:53.439 --> 00:57.305
yeah.

00:57.645 --> 00:58.667
Where did your dad come from? He came from Germany. 
What part of Germany? I don't remember. Did your

01:05.376 --> 01:06.938
mother come from Germany also? Yeah, she came too 
with his kids, yeah.

01:13.047 --> 01:13.187
Okay. So you only worked in the mines about six 
months? Yeah, I did. Yeah, Daddy, he worked long,

01:18.324 --> 01:21.187
you know. Yeah, he did. Well, did you actually go 
in, down inside the mine? Yeah, I went down in

01:27.833 --> 01:28.754
there. Yeah, I went down in there. What kind of 
tools did you use? Pick and shovel. Pick and

01:32.978 --> 01:33.779
shovel? Yeah, pick and shovel. Carbide lamps, you 
know. Yeah. Hang up here. Right, yeah. How many

01:40.445 --> 01:42.707
hours a day would you work on average? Ah, they 
wouldn't work more than me. Eight. Eight to five.

01:48.656 --> 01:49.597
That's about ten hours. Nine hours. Nine hours, 
yeah. Would you eat down inside the mine? Yeah,

01:56.848 --> 01:57.929
we'd eat down there. The Mexicans, they'd take 
their lunch along down there. They wouldn't come

02:02.616 --> 02:07.483
out until evening, you know, about four or five. I 
see. You lived at the mine site? Yeah, I lived out

02:11.108 --> 02:12.510
there. I was born out there. Could you describe the 
house in which you lived? The what? The house where

02:17.919 --> 02:20.682
you lived out there at the mines? What did it look 
like? Oh, it was an old house, kind of like this

02:22.704 --> 02:26.749
here, but you know. Was it painted or? No, it wasn't 
painted. No, it wasn't painted. Well, how many

02:32.716 --> 02:34.638
rooms were in the house?

02:39.223 --> 02:41.646
Lewis, you know how many rooms was in our house? How 
many rooms in our house? How many rooms in our

02:45.410 --> 02:48.835
house? Yeah. It's a big family. It was 12 kids in the 
family. What?

02:56.506 --> 02:57.047
Seven with the bag. Oh, she's talking about this 
house? What?

03:01.172 --> 03:02.214
Seven with the bag. Seven with the bag, at least she 
said. Out there at the mine. At the mine, yeah. And

03:08.182 --> 03:10.806
then they had two porches on it, you know, 
honestly. Old-time, you know how they used to have

03:11.157 --> 03:12.959
houses. It's kind of like these steps in the 
old-time house, too. You got two by sixes there.

03:18.626 --> 03:19.527
That's the old number. 42NC, that's later on, they 
made a letter. Right. See that? That's the old

03:24.153 --> 03:25.835
house, old number yet. Later on, they made that 
letter. Right. You know, played it. Uh-huh. Well,

03:32.383 --> 03:37.089
with this house out there, what years were you 
living out at Global Mine? Since I was born, I was

03:38.350 --> 03:40.793
born in 1900. 1900. We moved out here in 1919. How 
many years? So it's 19 years you lived at the mine

03:46.638 --> 03:50.525
site itself. I said we moved out here in 1919. I was 
born out here in 1900, December 21st. Did your

03:58.699 --> 04:01.583
father work in the mine all his life? No, he didn't.

04:07.975 --> 04:19.851
And then Grandpa, he opened up that lignite mine 
out there, so Daddy went to work for him. Grandpa?

04:21.694 --> 04:22.815
Grandpa Vogel, yeah. Grandpa Vogel. Yeah, he 
opened that lignite mine out here with coffee.

04:29.086 --> 04:30.508
clubhouse, I don't know if he went. He's about two 
miles from here. That's the first link that I might

04:33.351 --> 04:38.817
fix, they said, you know, on this side of the road, 
north side of the road. Right. Yeah, it's about two

04:40.139 --> 04:41.720
miles out here. Yeah, so daddy went to work for him, 
you know. Right. Went to work for him, him and

04:48.228 --> 04:56.597
grandpa's, you know, daughter, yeah, so they got 
married, you know. I see. Yeah, yeah. So your

04:59.174 --> 05:02.899
father married Grandpa Vogel's daughter? 
Daughter, yeah. I see. Yeah, that's Vogel's

05:04.281 --> 05:05.883
grandmother. My daddy's name is Lawrence, you 
know. Right. Vogel, yeah. They married,

05:09.348 --> 05:13.033
yeah. Well, what did your dad do at the mine? Was he a 
superintendent or a foreman? Yeah, he was kind of a

05:17.920 --> 05:22.186
foreman, yeah.

05:23.187 --> 05:25.090
Did you go to school out at the mines? School, 
school. Yeah, we were taught at which school?

05:30.157 --> 05:33.162
Excuse me, there at the Mines, or did you come in 
Rockdale? No, Talbert Ridge School. That is over

05:34.384 --> 05:35.005
here. I did the country. About two months you had to 
work. What was the name of that school? Talbert

05:39.853 --> 05:40.655
Ridge. Talbert? Talbert Ridge. T-A-L-B-E-R-T? 
Yeah, Talbert Ridge. Talbert Ridge. Did you go to

05:48.208 --> 05:54.418
school three, four months out of the year, or how 
long did you go to school? I was a full term.

06:00.363 --> 06:12.678
For the term, let me see, I guess from September, 
September till, I guess I could have got to school

06:00.363 --> 06:12.678
now almost about that long, I believe. Oh, you did? 
Did you like going to school out there? Yeah. Did

06:17.103 --> 06:17.383
you? Willie told me yesterday that he played hooky 
somewhere. Yeah, he never got there. He wouldn't

06:23.811 --> 06:25.213
go anywhere. He stayed in the woods, you know. But 
you liked to go to school? Yeah, I went to school. I

06:31.068 --> 06:37.575
went to seventh grade, I think, when I taught out

06:31.068 --> 06:37.575
in the country. Well, they had me play hooky, you 
know, and Daddy would take the bell out in the

06:37.615 --> 06:46.744
morning and finish school with us, you know, and 
lay it out in the woods till it even didn't come back

06:37.615 --> 06:46.744
home, you know. Well, he said he was sorry now he did 
that, you know, because he can't do it and write

06:48.285 --> 06:52.690
much. Yeah. I'm sure he learned a lot out there in 
the woods. I don't know, maybe. Well, did you get

07:00.404 --> 07:04.310
along with the Mexican families out there? Yeah, 
we done all right.

07:11.961 --> 07:18.111
Well, you lived in a big house then, comparatively 
speaking, to their houses. Can you remember how

07:18.131 --> 07:19.653
their houses lived? The other house, they had one 
room, one kitchen. One room, one kitchen? Yeah,

07:24.841 --> 07:27.525
just for the, you know, for the... Grandma owned 
them houses, you know, and she rented out to the

07:28.636 --> 07:33.303
Mexicans, you know. I see. Mine belonged to 
Grandpa. Grandma and them had them. I made about 30

07:41.634 --> 07:44.538
houses, I believe. The Mexicans, they paid rent 
every two weeks, you know. They weren't there but

07:48.284 --> 07:49.425
two weeks? They paid rent every two weeks. I see. 
They paid the Mexicans every two weeks. I see. Did

07:59.045 --> 08:04.655
you go into Rockdale very often or did you stay out 
of the mine camp most of the time? I stayed out there

08:04.675 --> 08:09.144
most of the time.

08:09.164 --> 08:13.091
So in 1919, what happened? Did you leave the mines 
then? No. And you came here? Yes. And you became a

08:16.978 --> 08:18.020
farmer? Yes, I was a farmer. Had you saved up some 
money to buy some land? No. Were you a

08:24.053 --> 08:26.777
sharecropper, or did you come with your father? I 
came with his dad, yeah. I see. So he was able to save

08:29.520 --> 08:34.507
up some money from working at the mines to buy his 
own land? Yeah, he got it all. We owed some of it. We

08:37.731 --> 08:42.978
got to pay it all, you know.

08:43.880 --> 08:46.964
Can you remember anything about the commissary 
out there at the mine? Yeah, kind of something,

08:48.446 --> 08:50.028
yeah. Do you remember what it looked like? It was 
just one room building, you know, just one room.

08:57.912 --> 09:04.279
Just made box lumber, you know, just plain 
building, you know. What kind of goods were sold at

09:04.299 --> 09:08.023
the commissary? Ah, they sold more just grocery 
stuff, I believe. No clothes or anything? No, I

09:13.729 --> 09:20.436
don't blame

09:13.729 --> 09:20.436
you. You were down there only six months, but you 
must remember some of the hazards of mining. Were

09:26.920 --> 09:30.204
there any dangers down there in the mines? Not too 
much. Down there, you know, some dirt would fall

09:31.185 --> 09:34.029
down. Tunnels, you know, tunnels about that wide, 
you know. So down there, some would cave down, you

09:37.613 --> 09:45.302
know, and they'd put props under there, you know, 
to keep from, you know, falling on the workers,

09:37.613 --> 09:45.302
yeah. How was the air down there? The air? Was the 
air bad to breathe, or...? It was pretty good. They

09:51.102 --> 09:55.810
had a fan, you know, what you call an air shaft, you 
know, on the other end of the fan, you know. Put the

09:55.830 --> 09:58.595
fresh air in and suck it out, you know. Sometimes 
it'd get bad. Sometimes it would. Had to, you know,

10:02.442 --> 10:04.085
fix it, though, you know. They make the air shafts 
or the air go, you know, circulating. Had a fan run

10:07.792 --> 10:13.963
by steam, you know, steam boiler, yeah. How did the 
Mexican workers work? Did they sing while they

10:17.661 --> 10:18.922
were working? Did they work together? Or did they 
work by themselves? Oh, each one worked

10:22.145 --> 10:23.546
separately. See, they got paid by those little 
cars, you know. They'd fill, you know, so and so

10:26.890 --> 10:28.652
much, you know. I don't remember how much they got. 
About 1,500 pounds in there. Little cars that run

10:32.936 --> 10:35.278
on little wheels, you know. Yeah. Little trucks 
put mules that pull to the shaft, you know. Right.

10:41.004 --> 10:42.065
They did work by them. The more they'd fill, you 
know, the more they'd make, you know. You see? And

10:45.584 --> 10:47.330
those other ones, they worked by the day. The other 
ones? The other ones, you know. Not one, but one to

10:50.520 --> 10:54.452
hose the coal up and down, you know. Right. Dump it 
out in the railroad car, you know. I see. Yeah. Then

10:58.443 --> 11:02.709
they had to have a man down in there, shove them cars 
on the cage, you know. So they pull it up and dump it

11:03.029 --> 11:05.933
down and let it back down. And those people, the men 
who ran the machinery were paid by the day? They

11:09.298 --> 11:10.099
were by the day. And the Mexicans and the other 
people who were down in the mines? Yeah, they

11:13.644 --> 11:15.587
worked by the car load, you know. I see. The more 
they fill, the more they make, you know. Were you a

11:19.292 --> 11:21.635
good miner when you were working down here? Did you 
mine a lot of coal every day? I didn't do much. I done

11:25.661 --> 11:27.083
pretty good, I guess, for it. my age, you know. I 
wasn't used to it much. How come you went down in the

11:32.517 --> 11:34.600
mines? What? How come you went down in the mines to 
work? Because I lived out there. You couldn't get a

11:41.930 --> 11:43.672
job working the machinery? I don't believe it. I 
wasn't old enough. I wasn't 18. I wasn't 18 yet.

11:50.982 --> 11:56.089
See, that here former, he wasn't allowed to work 
nobody unless he was 18 in the mines. I see. But that

11:56.780 --> 12:02.065
daddy fool, when he had to sign paper in case I got 
hurt or something, he couldn't complain, you

11:56.780 --> 12:02.065
know. Right. Well, do you remember Jose Morales? 
What? Do you remember Jose Morales? I don't

12:07.651 --> 12:10.594
believe I remember that Mexican. Well, he was 15 
years old in that big cave-in in 1913. The what? The

12:17.440 --> 12:18.181
cave-in. Yeah, cave-in, yeah. And he was 15 years 
old. Yeah. That was a little young then for— Yeah,

12:21.705 --> 12:25.048
it was young, but they had to— Oh, they couldn't 
work unless they was 18, you know. They had to sign

12:28.408 --> 12:31.290
in case they get hurt, you know. The boys get hurt, 
they couldn't, you know, pursue them or

12:32.151 --> 12:36.735
something, you know, complain, you know. I see. 
They took that chance, yeah. So Grandpa Vogel

12:39.958 --> 12:45.023
would make them sign these release forms. I see. Do 
you remember what the youngest Mexican worker you

12:46.144 --> 12:50.448
saw down there was? Adam B. was in it, and he owned 
it, that Adam B. And then Jose was in the Adam B. How

12:57.142 --> 12:58.885
did they use the mules? Did they take them down in 
the morning and bring them back? Yeah, bring them

13:01.709 --> 13:03.512
up back in the evening, yeah. Take them down and 
bring them back in the evening. Were they big

13:07.579 --> 13:09.302
mules, little mules? About medium size. About 
medium size, okay.

13:15.472 --> 13:19.118
Were they easy animals to work with? What? Were 
they easy animals? Yeah, they were easy tame

13:20.480 --> 13:23.605
mules. But they had many of them. They knew what to 
do, you know, what they had to do. Would you hitch

13:28.597 --> 13:31.621
the mule up to the small coal car? Yeah, car, and 
they'd pull it, you know. To the shaft? To the

13:34.666 --> 13:35.567
shaft, yeah. On the north side, they didn't have to 
hitch them in that way, going downhill and cool

13:36.949 --> 13:44.700
ones this way and that way, you know. To the east it 
goes downhill and south it goes down. This way goes

13:47.745 --> 13:49.267
up, you know. They had to pull the cars up here with 
the mules. It's just ridiculous, you know, coming

13:51.749 --> 13:57.318
down the road and down the side pushing. Was 
anybody hurt when you were down working in the

13:57.338 --> 13:59.902
mine? No, not that I know

13:59.922 --> 14:05.170
of. Did you pretty much stay to your own house or did 
you have Mexican friends when you were little? You

14:14.545 --> 14:17.390
know, did you socialize with them? Yeah, we got 
along with them, yeah. We didn't run around with

14:19.559 --> 14:24.165
some, you know, but there's some camp there, you 
know. How far away was the camp, the Mexican camp,

14:24.185 --> 14:28.471
from your house? Oh, it was close. It went too far. 
Some houses, some houses were, you know, some were

14:32.556 --> 14:35.740
close. What, about 50 yards or something like 
that? Yeah. Did, what kind of entertainment did

14:42.088 --> 14:45.613
the Mexicans have? Do you remember that? Did they 
sing or... If they had weddings, they'd dance, you

14:49.445 --> 14:53.409
know. They'd sing something. They would play 
guitar,

14:55.231 --> 14:59.775
you know. Let me ask you this. What, you know, 
mining must be really hard work. What? Mining must

15:05.461 --> 15:06.722
be really hard work. Yeah, it's hard work, yeah. So 
what did you eat, you know, in the morning before

15:08.104 --> 15:13.890
you went to the mine, and then at dinner, and then at 
supper? What kind of food did you eat? Ah, we just

15:15.736 --> 15:19.100
had like cream of wheat or something like that, you 
know. And for breakfast? Yeah. And what about for

15:21.042 --> 15:22.003
dinner? Ah, chicken or something else, like that 
meat, you know. Would you come up out of the mine to

15:27.248 --> 15:32.534
eat, or did you eat your dinner down in the mine? I 
came on home, then I went back. I see. And then for

15:37.520 --> 15:39.702
supper, what did you have? You wasn't in the mine 
much. You was just with Daddy. I told him I wasn't in

15:43.886 --> 15:45.388
that much. He was too young yet. I worked in a little 
while. I worked in a little while. They're not

15:51.686 --> 16:00.458
allowed to take their children or their sons down 
there to work unless, you know, they give

15:51.686 --> 16:00.458
permission. They have to be 18. They have to be 18 
before they can work in there, the boys. Unless

16:06.828 --> 16:09.011
their parents want to, you know. Right. Because if 
they might get hurt, they could sue them. This way

16:13.898 --> 16:15.460
they couldn't do that. By the way, are you Willie's 
wife? No, just a sister. I'm the second oldest.

16:22.725 --> 16:24.287
There's two girls. I've got a sister who lives 
uptown. She's a year older than I am. We're the two

16:29.755 --> 16:30.516
oldest. Then comes Willie. Are you Louise? 
Uh-huh. Louise Lawrence? Do y'all remember

16:37.285 --> 16:39.228
Gustav Vogel? Yes, she's our cousin. Your cousin. 
Gustav Miller. Why, you know her? No, I don't. I

16:46.824 --> 16:47.946
just, I heard about her. I was talking to Miss Beth 
the other day. Yes, she's my cousin. She's Gus

16:52.777 --> 16:54.461
Vogel's daughter. Is she still alive by any 
chance? Oh, no, she died 30 years ago or something

16:56.907 --> 17:01.998
like that. No, I may be. I understand she ran a 
little school for the Mexican children there.

17:07.290 --> 17:07.511
Yes. Do you remember anything? I don't know 
anything about the school business. I just know

17:12.016 --> 17:18.644
that Billy was out there at the mining camps too, 
and she'd come out there. She lived in town. Right.

17:21.247 --> 17:29.136
And she'd come out there and she'd teach them, but I 
don't know anything else about it. I guess they

17:29.156 --> 17:31.980
learned their English from Augusta. Uh-huh. You 
lived out at the mines with women. Do you remember?

17:39.646 --> 17:42.109
The whole family of us lived out there. My mother 
and dad and 14 children. 12 children, I think.

17:47.837 --> 17:50.080
There's 14 of us in all of them. My goodness. Do you 
remember any interesting stories, humor stories

17:52.303 --> 17:56.749
out there? You know, growing up or when you were 
older? Oh, well, we just played ball a whole lot. We

18:03.317 --> 18:14.530
went crawfishing in the caves, and friends would 
come out there, and we'd play marbles, and

18:03.317 --> 18:14.530
anything a boy would play, we'd play, too. Were 
most of your friends... We were mostly boys. Were

18:19.836 --> 18:24.862
most of your friends... We were nine girls, nine 
girls and three boys in our family. How did you put

18:25.202 --> 18:30.088
up with that, Willie?

18:31.570 --> 18:33.492
Were most of your friends in Rockdale? Oh, yeah, we 
know everybody in Rockdale. Did you have any

18:36.276 --> 18:39.279
friends out at the mine? Well, they wasn't just 
grown folks. They had very few children. Willie

18:47.429 --> 18:50.412
Helfer was one of them. Yeah, I talked to Willie 
yesterday. Yeah, he was my oldest sister's age, I

18:53.716 --> 18:58.422
believe. or a year older, and he and Willie chummed 
a lot. He'd come to our house, he and his folks.

19:09.070 --> 19:14.556
There wasn't very many white folks living out 
there, mostly, and Mexicans. Right. And we didn't

19:15.517 --> 19:18.941
have nothing to do with it. Oh, you didn't? Chum 
rockin' things out of maybe. Willie was telling me

19:25.435 --> 19:29.221
he learned Mexican, you know, the Spanish 
language really. Yeah. Daddy did too, and mother,

19:30.543 --> 19:35.750
and I can speak pretty good. I can tell you the name 
of any kind of vegetable. We sold them vegetables.

19:41.659 --> 19:44.003
We had a little express wagon, you know. Did you 
have a garden out by your house there? Yeah, we had a

19:46.026 --> 19:49.291
big garden and lots of pretty flowers. Daddy was a 
flower lover. He had lots of pretty flowers. We

19:54.123 --> 19:58.668
kids had to do the watering, you know. Well, did the 
Mexicans have their own gardens, too? Some, but

20:01.771 --> 20:03.773
they grown mostly... Hot peppers. Hot peppers 
and... Squash. Squash, something like that.

20:12.882 --> 20:15.184
Squash and what do you call them, cassaws? That's 
what they grown mostly. But you didn't have very

20:19.428 --> 20:21.731
much contact with the Mexicans? No, no. As far as 
speaking with them, you know, like you and I

20:23.907 --> 20:29.516
together, we couldn't do that. Oh, really? But we 
learned, you know, like good morning, good

20:30.758 --> 20:38.510
evening, and any kind of vegetable. Any kind of 
vegetable. Did many of them learn? We had cattle.

20:43.578 --> 20:46.543
We had cows, and we sold them milk and butter.

20:49.688 --> 20:51.611
And they paid you cash for it? Uh-huh. Did you trade 
at the commissary store? Yeah, there was a little

20:56.072 --> 21:03.306
one right in our house, our grandmother's house.

21:03.326 --> 21:06.112
And we did trading there. And they also had, in 
those days, The meat market in town here, he had a

21:12.760 --> 21:20.493
wagon team, and he'd come out there selling meat, 
go around the camp, sell meat. The ice man would

21:20.513 --> 21:22.356
come out and sell ice. The silver water man would 
come out there and sell soda water. The ice cream

21:26.383 --> 21:30.270
man would come out there. The lady sold bonnets and 
clothing. She'd come out there, take orders. You

21:38.900 --> 21:41.863
know, anybody that had something to sell had to 
come out there. Even the man at Christmas time

21:42.444 --> 21:46.548
would come with a whole load of Christmas trees. 
Oh, wow. And the Mexicans would buy Christmas

21:48.130 --> 21:50.433
trees? Yeah, yeah. Some of them had horses and 
buggies of their own, and some didn't. We all

22:00.043 --> 22:03.287
walked the town a lot, you know. I said it was three 
miles. I don't know how far it was. It really was.

22:10.412 --> 22:11.894
I'd say it was three miles. And we'd walk along the 
railroad or along the dirt road. It wasn't but a

22:18.122 --> 22:20.565
dirt road. It wasn't down then. But after 1919, 
y'all didn't do any more mining? No, we moved out

22:25.731 --> 22:29.416
here then, 1919. Do you prefer farming to mining? 
Yes. Why is that? Well, the doctor told Daddy he had

22:36.319 --> 22:41.105
to get out of that hole. He wouldn't live there 
long. Why was that?

22:46.211 --> 22:48.694
Did he pick up a disease or something? No, you know, 
but... He'd always get headaches, so I guess that A

22:49.735 --> 22:52.038
in there. The gas, you know, mines have gas in them. 
Yeah, the headache, you know. So your Daddy went

22:56.784 --> 22:58.466
down in the mine? Uh-huh. He was a... kind of boss of 
the Mexicans. Grandfather made him boss. Did he

23:06.465 --> 23:08.189
have any trouble with Mexicans? No. That's where 
he learned to speak Spanish, you know. I see.

23:17.709 --> 23:18.511
We're German. Right. And we could speak, us older 
kids all learned how to speak German. And then we

23:26.133 --> 23:30.162
learned how to speak some Spanish and English. We 
could speak three languages. Grandmother used

23:34.010 --> 23:39.964
to, in the First World War I was on, She took German 
newspapers. And her children all got married and

23:43.342 --> 23:49.112
left home and left her there by herself. So mother 
said, from now on, you and Martha are going to have

23:49.132 --> 23:58.508
to go one night you go, stay with them, and the other 
night Louise go and stay with them. So we did that.

24:00.700 --> 24:05.768
Every night she'd read the news to us in German, you 
know, tell us what it's about. About the war. And I

24:07.732 --> 24:10.496
got so I really could live, too. The newspaper 
writing, you know, print is more like in German.

24:16.917 --> 24:21.802
